00:07:38.130 --> 00:07:42.250
So starting from, kind
of, the beginning rather.

00:07:42.250 --> 00:07:45.290
In 2014, there was a
Northwest transmission line

00:07:45.290 --> 00:07:47.940
completed in British Columbia.

00:07:47.940 --> 00:07:50.400
Northwest British
Columbia is an area

00:07:50.400 --> 00:07:53.037
that has about 2,000 people.

00:07:53.037 --> 00:07:55.120
So it's, kind of, in the
middle of nowhere, right.

00:07:55.120 --> 00:07:57.960
And so when this power
line was completed,

00:07:57.960 --> 00:08:02.150
it created this
chaotic craze, rather,

00:08:02.150 --> 00:08:06.370
to start development to start
any type of project that

00:08:06.370 --> 00:08:08.310
could be started.

00:08:08.310 --> 00:08:11.200
73% of the world's
mining companies

00:08:11.200 --> 00:08:13.600
are based in Vancouver.

00:08:13.600 --> 00:08:17.220
So that's just one start
of this flow and momentum.

00:08:17.220 --> 00:08:20.810
And then also, the former
prime minister of Canada,

00:08:20.810 --> 00:08:23.040
Harper, under his
administration,

00:08:23.040 --> 00:08:27.170
all federal environmental
regulations were deregulated.

00:08:27.170 --> 00:08:30.680
And this created, kind of, a
free for all, more or less,

00:08:30.680 --> 00:08:34.330
for exploration of development.

00:08:34.330 --> 00:08:39.480
And if you look at different
websites and different maps,

00:08:39.480 --> 00:08:43.770
I think that-- can
we go to the map?

00:08:43.770 --> 00:08:45.240
It's just a slew.

00:08:45.240 --> 00:08:48.210
There's a plethora of
different projects ranging.

00:08:48.210 --> 00:08:53.580
Different types of mining
all throughout the region.

00:08:53.580 --> 00:08:56.140
But we, the Salmon
Beyond Borders campaign,

00:08:56.140 --> 00:09:00.400
is primarily focused on this
Northwest, British Columbia,

00:09:00.400 --> 00:09:02.950
Southeast, Alaska region.

00:09:02.950 --> 00:09:04.950
And again, I'm
from Juneau, which

00:09:04.950 --> 00:09:07.490
is on this side of the map.

00:09:07.490 --> 00:09:08.780
It's the capital of Alaska.

00:09:08.780 --> 00:09:11.030
We have about 30,000 people.

00:09:11.030 --> 00:09:15.040
And in Southeast Alaska, there's
about 75,000 people total.

00:09:15.040 --> 00:09:18.230
On that side of the other
side of the border in British

00:09:18.230 --> 00:09:20.070
Columbia, there's 2,000.

00:09:20.070 --> 00:09:27.100
So again, it's not a
heavily populated area.

00:09:27.100 --> 00:09:29.190
And the size itself
is similar to that

00:09:29.190 --> 00:09:30.700
of the country of France.

00:09:30.700 --> 00:09:33.817
So it's this gigantic region.

00:09:33.817 --> 00:09:34.650
Not a lot of people.

00:09:34.650 --> 00:09:37.580
Not a lot of people
know about it.

00:09:37.580 --> 00:09:40.790
And there are these different
mines that we're focusing on.

00:09:40.790 --> 00:09:44.160
Again, 10 because of their
size, scale, and scope,

00:09:44.160 --> 00:09:48.420
and their proximity
to Alaska that we're

00:09:48.420 --> 00:09:52.680
highlighting and working to
raise awareness for because we

00:09:52.680 --> 00:09:53.820
don't have any say.

00:09:53.820 --> 00:09:57.060
As downstream interests, those
of us in Southeast Alaska,

00:09:57.060 --> 00:10:00.140
there are no established
protections for us

00:10:00.140 --> 00:10:03.970
to protect and ensure long-term
water quality and enforceable

00:10:03.970 --> 00:10:07.850
protections to our fisheries
and the industries that

00:10:07.850 --> 00:10:10.850
keep Alaska going in Southeast.

00:10:10.850 --> 00:10:13.050
So again, I'll give
you a quick example.

00:10:13.050 --> 00:10:17.300
The KSM Project, which is down
here in the Unuk watershed,

00:10:17.300 --> 00:10:21.400
that project was approved by
the provincial and federal

00:10:21.400 --> 00:10:22.520
governments in Canada.

00:10:22.520 --> 00:10:26.840
It would be the largest open
pit mine in North America

00:10:26.840 --> 00:10:28.570
and the fifth
largest in the world.

00:10:28.570 --> 00:10:32.940
That's 19 miles
upstream from Alaska.

00:10:32.940 --> 00:10:34.760
And it runs into
Misty Fjords National

00:10:34.760 --> 00:10:38.740
Monument, which is a federally
protected area, obviously.

00:10:38.740 --> 00:10:42.590
And I'll mention also that all
of Southeast Alaska-- this area

00:10:42.590 --> 00:10:44.860
through here-- is under
protection of the Tongass

00:10:44.860 --> 00:10:47.420
National Forest, which is
the largest National Forest

00:10:47.420 --> 00:10:48.860
in the United States.

00:10:48.860 --> 00:10:52.940
So on our side, the United
States side of these rivers,

00:10:52.940 --> 00:10:55.300
you have the largest
or the highest level

00:10:55.300 --> 00:10:56.840
of federal protections.

00:10:56.840 --> 00:11:00.640
And on the BC side,
it's under development.

00:11:00.640 --> 00:11:04.380
The current premier of British
Columbia, Christy Clark,

00:11:04.380 --> 00:11:06.260
wanted her legacy to
be in this region.

00:11:06.260 --> 00:11:07.730
10 mines in 10 years.

00:11:07.730 --> 00:11:12.140
And she's exceeded that as far
as what stages of development

00:11:12.140 --> 00:11:14.490
these mines are in.

00:11:14.490 --> 00:11:17.400
So again, our main
ask is that we're

00:11:17.400 --> 00:11:20.260
raising awareness to this
issue, to this region that

00:11:20.260 --> 00:11:21.350
is unpopulated.

00:11:21.350 --> 00:11:24.490
That we're giving a voice
to the commercial fishermen,

00:11:24.490 --> 00:11:27.950
to the tribal governments,
to the tour operators that

00:11:27.950 --> 00:11:31.000
rely on healthy
fisheries and clean water

00:11:31.000 --> 00:11:36.540
to continue to draw tourists and
fishermen in for sport fishing.

00:11:36.540 --> 00:11:39.210
So we, over the years,
have been trying

00:11:39.210 --> 00:11:43.850
to figure out what type
of enforceable mechanisms,

00:11:43.850 --> 00:11:45.990
different policies,
international policies,

00:11:45.990 --> 00:11:49.290
are out there and available to
influence these standards that

00:11:49.290 --> 00:11:53.000
will guarantee protections
for generations to come.

00:11:53.000 --> 00:11:54.310
And really, that's our target.

00:11:54.310 --> 00:11:58.440
That's our ask is that under the
Boundary Waters Treaty, which

00:11:58.440 --> 00:12:01.740
was signed by both
countries in 1909,

00:12:01.740 --> 00:12:06.140
we have the authority to have
a say as United States citizens

00:12:06.140 --> 00:12:08.800
and downstream
stakeholders in Alaska

00:12:08.800 --> 00:12:12.790
to determine how these globally
significant watersheds are

00:12:12.790 --> 00:12:14.430
developed.

00:12:14.430 --> 00:12:17.930
So again, just trying to
get that seat at the table.

00:12:17.930 --> 00:12:22.350
It's a complex,
convoluted issue involving

00:12:22.350 --> 00:12:26.760
different international laws
and different interests.

00:12:26.760 --> 00:12:29.360
But it's been an
incredible issue

00:12:29.360 --> 00:12:32.420
in that it has brought together
all sectors of Southeast

00:12:32.420 --> 00:12:35.720
Alaska ranging from the tribal
governments to the business

00:12:35.720 --> 00:12:39.220
owners to our
congressional delegation.

00:12:39.220 --> 00:12:44.190
Alaska's congressional
delegation, which are all ours,

00:12:44.190 --> 00:12:47.270
very strong conservatives
have supported us

00:12:47.270 --> 00:12:49.680
through this effort
in a sense that this

00:12:49.680 --> 00:12:51.630
is our way of life
in Southeast Alaska

00:12:51.630 --> 00:12:53.350
and the majority of the state.

00:12:53.350 --> 00:12:54.950
Salmon is our way of life.

00:12:54.950 --> 00:12:58.910
In Southeast Alaska alone,
there's a $2 billion industry.

00:12:58.910 --> 00:13:01.960
Commercial fishing,
$1 billion annually.

00:13:01.960 --> 00:13:04.490
Tourism, $1 billion annually.

00:13:04.490 --> 00:13:08.150
These industries are dependent
upon these clean waters.

00:13:08.150 --> 00:13:12.470
And we maintain that we should
have a say in how these shared

00:13:12.470 --> 00:13:14.480
watersheds are developed.

00:13:14.480 --> 00:13:17.190
So getting back to the
fact that it is clunky

00:13:17.190 --> 00:13:19.350
and before I continue
to ramble, we

00:13:19.350 --> 00:13:21.480
have explored
different ways in which

00:13:21.480 --> 00:13:23.270
we can help tell our story.

00:13:23.270 --> 00:13:24.390
How do we raise awareness?

00:13:24.390 --> 00:13:28.390
How do we get someone in the
middle of the United States

00:13:28.390 --> 00:13:31.330
or a Bay Area of California
to really care or be

00:13:31.330 --> 00:13:33.770
aware of this issue?

00:13:33.770 --> 00:13:39.110
And through that, we have had
great contacts with filmmakers,

00:13:39.110 --> 00:13:43.880
and brother-in-laws working
for Google, and chefs.

00:13:43.880 --> 00:13:47.230
Throughout the country,
it's been extraordinary.

